Mars Regolith-Based Habitat Architecture

A Theoretical Framework for ISRU-Driven Extraterrestrial Settlement Design

ouadi Maakoul 
---

Abstract

This dissertation proposes a comprehensive theoretical framework for the design and economic assessment of Martian surface habitats constructed primarily from in-situ resources. The architecture is derived from first principles of radiation transport physics, structural mechanics, and thermo-economic optimization, without reliance on empirical data from physical experimentation. A hybrid structural decoupling approach is proposed, wherein an outer shell of processed Martian regolith would provide environmental shielding and micrometeorite protection, while an inner pressurized module would maintain a habitable atmosphere. Closed-form analytical models and parametric numerical analyses are developed to quantify the anticipated cost drivers. The work demonstrates, through rigorous mathematical derivation, that interplanetary transport mass is expected to dominate all other economic considerations by several orders of magnitude—a finding formalized herein as the Transport Dominance Principle. This theoretical foundation is intended to guide future experimental validation, technology development, and mission architecture planning for sustainable human presence on Mars.

Keywords: Mars habitat, In-Situ Resource Utilization, radiation shielding, structural mechanics, cost modeling, theoretical architecture, space systems engineering

---

1. Introduction

1.1 Motivation and Problem Statement

The establishment of a sustainable human presence on Mars presents a formidable economic challenge. The cost of transporting mass from Earth's surface to the Martian surface is expected to remain the dominant constraint on all mission architectures for the foreseeable future. Current projections for cargo transport to the Martian surface, based on next-generation reusable launch vehicle concepts, place the specific transport cost $c_T$ in the range of $10^4$ to $10^5$ United States dollars per kilogram for early missions. At these costs, a modest habitat of 100 m² floor area constructed entirely from Earth-imported materials would require capital expenditure measured in tens of billions of dollars for structural and shielding components alone.

This economic reality compels a fundamental rethinking of construction methodology. The proposed solution lies in In-Situ Resource Utilization—the practice of harvesting and processing local materials to replace Earth-imported mass. Mars offers an abundant, globally distributed resource in its regolith: the layer of loose, unconsolidated material covering the bedrock, produced by billions of years of impact gardening and aeolian processes. The theoretical potential of regolith as a construction material forms the central premise of this investigation.

1.2 Research Objectives and Scope

This dissertation proposes to develop a comprehensive theoretical architecture for Martian habitats that would maximize ISRU while maintaining structural integrity, radiation protection, and habitable volume. The specific objectives of this work are:

1. To formulate a quantitative cost model that explicitly captures the trade-off between local processing energy and transport mass, thereby demonstrating the anticipated dominance of transport costs.
2. To develop a detailed structural analysis of a proposed decoupled outer-shell and inner-habitat architecture, including finite element validation of critical load cases using assumed material properties derived from the literature.
3. To conduct a radiological shielding analysis based on established transport codes and published Martian surface radiation models, determining the required regolith thickness for adequate crew protection.
4. To outline a conceptual construction workflow optimized for autonomous, pre-human deployment.
5. To perform sensitivity analyses that quantify the impact of varying launch cost projections, processing energy assumptions, and alternative ISRU pathways on the overall economic case.

This work is purely theoretical and analytical. No physical experimentation or construction is claimed, nor are any experimental results presented. All numerical values are derived from fundamental physical principles or adopted as parametric assumptions from the open literature for the purpose of illustration and sensitivity analysis.

1.3 Contributions of This Work

The primary contributions of this dissertation to the body of knowledge are:

· The formal articulation and mathematical proof of the Transport Dominance Principle, which establishes that the cost of transporting mass from Earth exceeds all other habitat construction costs by orders of magnitude across all plausible parameter ranges.
· A closed-form cost model for ISRU-based habitat construction that explicitly includes amortization of fixed infrastructure, enabling breakeven analysis and sensitivity studies.
· A validated structural decoupling architecture that separates environmental shielding functions from pressurization functions, allowing independent optimization of each subsystem.
· A parametric framework for radiation shielding design that accounts for the secondary neutron buildup effect at intermediate depths.
· A comprehensive set of sensitivity analyses that demonstrate the robustness of the ISRU economic case across a wide range of assumptions.

1.4 Document Organization

This dissertation proceeds as follows. Section 2 provides a review of prior art and the current state of research in Martian ISRU habitat concepts. Section 3 establishes the theoretical foundations, including radiation physics, structural mechanics, and thermo-economic optimization. Section 4 presents the proposed hybrid architecture in detail. Section 5 develops the first-order cost model and presents quantitative results based on parametric assumptions. Section 6 contains the structural and radiological validation calculations. Section 7 details a proposed construction workflow. Section 8 discusses anticipated engineering challenges and potential mitigation strategies. Section 9 presents sensitivity analyses and alternative scenarios. Section 10 outlines future research directions necessary for validation. Section 11 concludes with a vision for scalable Martian infrastructure.

