2. Literature Review and State of the Art

2.1 NASA and ESA Habitat Development Concepts

The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has systematically advanced ISRU habitat concepts through multiple programmatic channels. The 3D-Printed Habitat Challenge, conducted from 2015 to 2019, awarded $3.15 million in prize money across multiple phases and culminated in the printing of a one-third-scale habitat structure by AI SpaceFactory's "MARSHA" design. This competition demonstrated the feasibility of autonomous additive construction using minimal imported materials, though the present work does not rely on any specific proprietary data from that effort.

Concurrently, NASA's Crew Health and Performance Exploration Analog (CHAPEA) missions have been conducting long-duration isolation studies in a 1,700-square-foot 3D-printed habitat at Johnson Space Center. These missions provide context for the relevance of habitat design research, though human-factors data are not incorporated directly into this theoretical study.

The European Space Agency, in collaboration with Foster and Partners, has developed conceptual designs for lunar and Martian habitats that would employ autonomous robots to excavate craters or construct regolith-based shells over inflatable modules. The "excavate, inflate, cover" approach informs the architectural concept proposed herein.

2.2 Radiation Shielding Research

The radiation environment on the Martian surface presents a unique challenge. Mars lacks a global magnetic field and possesses only a thin atmosphere of approximately 6–10 mbar surface pressure, providing minimal attenuation of galactic cosmic rays and solar energetic particles. Surface radiation measurements from the Radiation Assessment Detector (RAD) aboard the Mars Science Laboratory have quantified this environment: the average absorbed dose rate ranges from approximately 0.21 mGy/day at solar maximum to 0.32 mGy/day at solar minimum.

The transport of GCR through Martian regolith has been modeled extensively using NASA's OLTARIS tool and the underlying HZETRN transport code. Zhang et al. (2022) conducted comprehensive simulations showing that 1–2 meters of regolith would be necessary to reduce effective doses to below 50–100 mSv/yr across varying surface elevations. An important counterintuitive effect occurs at shallow depths: secondary neutron flux is predicted to increase as GCR primaries interact with regolith nuclei, peaking at approximately 30 cm depth. This necessitates either very shallow or deeper shielding, as intermediate depths may increase rather than decrease certain radiation components.

2.3 Regolith Processing Pathways in Literature

Multiple processing pathways have been proposed in the literature for transforming raw Martian regolith into construction materials. This work does not advocate for any specific technology but treats the specific processing energy as a parametric variable. The following pathways are noted for context:

· Thermal Sintering: Heating regolith to 1,100–1,200°C to cause particle fusion through solid-state diffusion.
· Cold Sintering Process: A recently proposed alternative operating at 120–200°C using transient liquid phases and applied pressure.
· Sulfur Concrete: Using elemental sulfur as a thermoplastic binder for regolith aggregates.
· Geopolymerization: Alkaline activation of aluminosilicate-rich regolith to produce cementitious materials.

The present work treats the specific processing energy $e_P$ as a variable to be explored through sensitivity analysis, rather than relying on any single reported experimental value.

2.4 Economic Modeling of ISRU

Several studies have attempted to quantify the economic breakeven point for ISRU adoption. A 2023 analysis in Acta Astronautica modeled mass-to-orbit requirements and concluded that ISRU would become favorable when cumulative constructed area exceeds approximately 500–1,000 m². The present work extends this type of analysis by developing an explicit cost function and parametric sensitivity study.

The Moon to Mars Architecture Definition Document released by NASA in 2023 identifies ISRU as a foundational capability for sustainable lunar and Martian presence, defining Class III habitats as those constructed primarily from indigenous resources. The architecture proposed herein corresponds to a Class III approach.

2.5 Identified Gaps and Contributions of This Work

Despite significant prior conceptual work, several areas require more rigorous theoretical treatment:

1. An explicit mathematical formulation linking radiation shielding requirements, structural design parameters, and economic variables.
2. A systematic parametric exploration of how variations in key assumptions affect the economic case.
3. A clear articulation of the structural decoupling principle with quantitative validation.

This work addresses these gaps through purely analytical and computational methods.

