5. First-Order Cost Model

5.1 Cost Model Formulation

The total cost per square meter of habitable floor area is modeled as:

C_{\text{total}} = C_{\text{energy}} + C_{\text{robotics}} + C_{\text{transport}} + C_{\text{systems}} + C_{\text{amortized}}

For parametric analysis, a baseline transport cost of $c_T = 100,000 \text{ \$/kg}$ is adopted, consistent with current projections for early cargo missions to the Martian surface using next-generation launch systems. This value is treated as a variable in sensitivity analysis.

5.2 Regolith Processing Energy Cost

The energy required per square meter is:

E_{\text{m²}} = m_{\text{regolith}} \cdot e_P

For the proposed design, $m_{\text{regolith}} = \rho \cdot \bar{h} \approx 1,400 \cdot 2.14 \approx 3,000 \text{ kg/m²}$. With $e_P = 0.40 \text{ kWh/kg}$:

E_{\text{m²}} = 3,000 \cdot 0.40 = 1,200 \text{ kWh/m²}

The cost of energy on Mars would include generation and storage amortization. A representative value of $c_E = 0.50 \text{ \$/kWh}$ is assumed. Thus:

C_{\text{energy}} = 1,200 \cdot 0.50 = 600 \text{ \$/m²}

5.3 Robotics and Infrastructure Amortization

A notional robotics suite for autonomous construction is assumed with the following mass breakdown:

