6. Structural and Radiological Validation Calculations

6.1 Finite Element Analysis of Proposed Outer Shell

A finite element model of the proposed catenary dome would be constructed with the following parameters:

· Geometry: Axisymmetric catenary profile, $R_{\text{base}} = 5 \text{ m}$, $H_{\text{apex}} = 4 \text{ m}$
· Thickness: Variable, $t(r) = 2.1 + 0.5(r/5)^2 \text{ m}$
· Material properties (assumed for sintered regolith):
  · Compressive strength: $f_c = 80 \text{ MPa}$
  · Tensile strength: $f_t = 8 \text{ MPa}$
  · Elastic modulus: $E = 30 \text{ GPa}$
  · Poisson's ratio: $\nu = 0.20$
  · Density: $\rho = 1,400 \text{ kg/m³}$

The following load cases would be analyzed:

Load Case 1: Self-Weight Only

· Gravity: $g = 3.71 \text{ m/s²}$ (vertical, downward)
· Predicted maximum compressive stress: $\sigma_{\text{max}} \approx 0.14 \text{ MPa}$
· Utilization ratio: $0.14 / 80 = 0.0018$ (0.18%)

Load Case 2: Self-Weight + Thermal Gradient

· Diurnal temperature variation: $\Delta T = 80 \text{ K}$
· Coefficient of thermal expansion: $\alpha = 8 \times 10^{-6} \text{ K}^{-1}$
· Predicted maximum tensile stress: $\sigma_{\text{thermal}} = E \alpha \Delta T \approx 19.2 \text{ MPa}$ (assuming full restraint)
· With partial restraint, estimated at $\sigma_t \approx 2.4 \text{ MPa}$
· Utilization ratio: $2.4 / 8.0 = 0.30$ (30%)

Load Case 3: Self-Weight + Seismic (Marsquake)

· Seismic acceleration: $a = 0.05g$ (horizontal)
· Predicted maximum compressive stress: $\approx 0.21 \text{ MPa}$
· Utilization ratio: 0.26%

Conclusion: The proposed shell geometry is predicted to operate at low utilization ratios under self-weight and seismic loads. Thermal cycling would produce the most significant stresses, approaching approximately 30% of assumed tensile capacity. Mitigation strategies such as expansion joints or fiber reinforcement may be warranted.

6.2 Radiation Shielding Performance Analysis

Using the simplified attenuation model with $\lambda = 70 \text{ g/cm²}$ and the buildup factor from Section 3.1.3, the transmitted dose fraction is:

Depth $h$ (m) Areal Density $x$ (g/cm²) Dose Fraction $f_D$
0 0 1.00
0.36 50 ~1.12 (neutron peak)
0.71 100 0.41
1.43 200 0.24
2.14 300 0.16
2.86 400 0.09
3.57 500 0.05

For a crew member spending 80% of time within the shielded habitat and 20% in unshielded locations:

D_{\text{annual, absorbed}} = 0.8 \cdot D_0 \cdot f_D + 0.2 \cdot D_0

Using $D_0 = 76.7 \text{ mGy/yr}$ (based on RAD measurements) and $f_D = 0.16$:

D_{\text{annual, absorbed}} = 0.8 \cdot 76.7 \cdot 0.16 + 0.2 \cdot 76.7 = 9.8 + 15.3 = 25.1 \text{ mGy/yr}

Converting to effective dose using a radiation weighting factor $w_R \approx 3.0$ for the GCR environment:

H_{\text{annual}} = 25.1 \cdot 3.0 = 75.3 \text{ mSv/yr}

This value falls well below the occupational limit of 500 mSv/yr and would preserve career limits for multi-mission astronauts.

