Appendix J: Mathematical Proofs of the Transport Dominance Principle

J.1 Formal Statement

Transport Dominance Principle: For extraterrestrial construction, there exists a threshold transport cost $c_T^*$ such that for all $c_T > c_T^*$, the optimal construction strategy is to maximize ISRU utilization regardless of local energy cost $c_E$ and processing efficiency $e_P$, within physically plausible bounds.

J.2 Proof

Consider the cost per unit area of a habitat component:

C_{\text{ISRU}} = c_E \cdot e_P \cdot m_{\text{local}} + \frac{C_{\text{fixed}}}{A}

C_{\text{import}} = c_T \cdot m_{\text{local}}

The condition for ISRU to be economically favorable is:

c_E \cdot e_P \cdot m_{\text{local}} + \frac{C_{\text{fixed}}}{A} < c_T \cdot m_{\text{local}}

Rearranging:

c_T > c_E \cdot e_P + \frac{C_{\text{fixed}}}{A \cdot m_{\text{local}}}

Let $c_T^*$ be the right-hand side. For realistic parameters:

· Upper bound on $c_E$: Solar/nuclear power on Mars, $c_E \leq 10 \text{ \$/kWh}$
· Upper bound on $e_P$: Complete melting of regolith, $e_P \leq 3 \text{ kWh/kg}$ (thermodynamic limit)
· Lower bound on $A$: Smallest viable habitat, $A \geq 10 \text{ m²}$
· Lower bound on $m_{\text{local}}$: Minimal shielding, $m_{\text{local}} \geq 100 \text{ kg/m²}$
· Upper bound on $C_{\text{fixed}}$: Development cost, $C_{\text{fixed}} \leq 10^9 \text{ \$}$

Then:

c_T^* \leq 10 \cdot 3 + \frac{10^9}{10 \cdot 100} = 30 + 10^6 = 1,000,030 \text{ \$/kg}

This is approximately $1 \text{ M\$/kg}$.

Current and projected Mars transport costs are $c_T \approx 10^4 - 10^5 \text{ \$/kg}$. Even the most pessimistic upper bound for $c_T^*$ is an order of magnitude below current projections. Therefore, for all foreseeable launch systems:

c_T \ll c_T^*

The inequality is satisfied by a factor of at least 10–100. Thus, ISRU is strictly dominant.

J.3 Corollary: Energy Independence

The Transport Dominance Principle implies that the choice of ISRU processing technology is largely insensitive to energy efficiency. The ratio of total cost difference between processing methods to total habitat cost is:

\frac{\Delta C}{C_{\text{total}}} = \frac{m_{\text{local}} \cdot c_E \cdot \Delta e_P}{m_{\text{import}} \cdot c_T} \ll 1

For $\Delta e_P = 1 \text{ kWh/kg}$, $m_{\text{local}} = 3,000 \text{ kg/m²}$, $m_{\text{import}} = 65 \text{ kg/m²}$:

\frac{\Delta C}{C_{\text{total}}} = \frac{3,000 \cdot 0.5 \cdot 1}{65 \cdot 100,000} = \frac{1,500}{6,500,000} \approx 0.00023 = 0.023\%

Thus, a 100% increase in processing energy changes total cost by less than 0.05%. Technology selection should prioritize reliability, autonomy, and construction speed over energy efficiency.

J.4 Generalization to Other Resources

The principle extends to any resource where:

\frac{\text{Local production cost}}{\text{Transport cost}} \ll 1

This includes water extraction from regolith or ice deposits, oxygen production from atmospheric CO₂, and manufacturing of structural components from local materials. The principle provides a unified framework for ISRU investment decisions.

